{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508668"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:08:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:08:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11349"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11349"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.05,0.21,0.02,0.69]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"3994"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51276"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"3994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/3994"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11349"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36557"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"92"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3820"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3828"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14536"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43866"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51276"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of general malaise. He has noticed increasing fatigue by the end of the day and intermittent, non-specific abdominal discomfort during this time. He has a medical history of hypertension for which he takes perindopril. He works as a carpenter. He drinks four to five beers on Saturday nights and has a 10 pack-year smoking history. He has no history of intravenous drug use but had tattoos done in both Australia and Bali during his 30s.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. He has jaundiced sclera and a liver edge palpable 2 cm below the costal margin. Heart sounds are dual with no murmur, and lungs are clear bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EALT: 698 U/L (0-55)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAST: 356 U/L (0-45)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EALP: 88 U/L (30-110)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGGT: 75 U/L (0-60)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETotal bilirubin: 38 \u00b5mol/L (3-20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHBsAg: Positive\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAnti-HBc IgM: Negative\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAnti-HBc IgG: Positive\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAnti-HBs: Negative\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHBeAg: Positive\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHAV-IgG: Positive\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute hepatitis E infection","Acute hepatitis A infection","Acute hepatitis B infection","Previous hepatitis B vaccination","Chronic hepatitis B infection"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with non-specific signs of hepatitis from a chronic hepatitis B infection, due to a likely infective event from his tattoo acquisition overseas many years ago. The common routes of transmission for HBV include mother-child transmission (vertical transmission), sexual contact and blood contact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic hepatitis B infection\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis based on the serology results. The presence of positive HBsAg, anti-HBc IgG, along with negative anti-HBs and anti-HBc IgM, is characteristic of chronic hepatitis B infection. Positive HBeAg indicates active viral replication, resulting in hepatocellular damage. This is supported by elevated liver enzymes (ALT \u0026gt; AST) with normal ALP. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute hepatitis E infection\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely in this case. While it can cause similar symptoms and liver enzyme elevations, the hepatitis B serology results clearly point towards chronic hepatitis B, and hepatitis E serology has not been presented; HBeAg refers to the hepatitis B envelope antigen, rather than hepatitis E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute hepatitis A infection\u003C/strong\u003E is ruled out by the positive HAV-IgG, which indicates past hepatitis A infection or vaccination, not an acute infection. Moreover, the hepatitis B serology is inconsistent with acute hepatitis A.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute hepatitis B infection\u003C/strong\u003E is not consistent with the serology results. In acute hepatitis B, we would expect to see positive anti-HBc IgM, which is negative in this case. The negative anti-HBc IgM and positive anti-HBc IgG suggest a long-standing infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevious hepatitis B vaccination\u003C/strong\u003E would result in positive anti-HBs and negative HBsAg, which is not the case here. The positive HBsAg indicates active infection, not immunity from vaccination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA summary of the hepatitis B serology is as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHBsAg: Acute or chronic infection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-HBc IgM: Acute infection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-HBc IgG: Past or present infection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-HBs: Vaccination or cleared infection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHBeAg: Active viral replication\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Presence of positive HBsAg and anti-HBc IgG indicate a chronic hepatitis B infection.","Elevated ALT and AST with normal ALP suggest hepatocellular injury rather than cholestatic liver disease."],"references":["Jameson JL, Fauci AS, Kasper DL, Hauser SL, Longo DL and Loscalzo J. Harrison\u0027s Principles of Internal Medicine. 20th ed. McGraw-Hill Education, 2018. pg.","Lok, A. Hepatitis B virus: Clinical manifestations and natural history [Internet]. Uptodate; 2020 [updated 2020; cited 2021 Sep 12]. Available from: \u003Chttps://www-uptodate-com.ezproxy.flinders.edu.au/contents/hepatitis-b-virus-clinical-manifestations-and-natural-history?search=hepatitis%20B\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=3~150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=3#H1579639390\u003E.","Lok, A. Hepatitis B virus: Screening and diagnosis [Internet]. Uptodate; 2021 [updated 2021; cited 2021 12 Sep]. Available from: \u003Chttps://www-uptodate-com.ezproxy.flinders.edu.au/contents/hepatitis-b-virus-screening-and-diagnosis?search=hepatitis%20B\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=2~150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=2#H2753994324\u003E.","Towell, V. and Cowie, B. Hepatitis B serology [Internet]. RACGP; 2021 [cited 2021 Sep 12]. Available from: ,https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/april/hepatitis-b-serology/\u003E.","Lai M and Chopra S. Hepatitis A virus infection in adults: Epidemiology, clinical manifestations, and diagnosis [Internet]. Uptodate; 2021 [updated 2021; cited 2021 Sep 12]. Available from: \u003Chttps://www-uptodate-com.ezproxy.flinders.edu.au/contents/hepatitis-a-virus-infection-in-adults-epidemiology-clinical-manifestations-and-diagnosis?search=hepatitis%20A\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1#H3024115574\u003E."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36557"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11349"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36557"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-23T11:41:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-23T11:43:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"3994"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51276"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"